and it is often seen as a unified, coherent, and inevitable advancement. Laugier questions this assumption, rethinking the very grounds that drove analytic philosophy to develop and uncovering its inherent tensions and confusions. Drawing on J. L. Austin and the later works of Ludwig Wittgenstein, she argues for the solution provided by ordinary language philosophy—a philosophy that trusts and utilizes the everyday use of language and the clarity of meaning it provides—and in doing so offers a major contribution to the philosophy of language and twentieth- and twenty-first-century philosophy as a whole.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAnalysis (Philosophy) 0aAnalysis (Philosophy). 0aLanguage and languagesxPhilosophy. 0aPhilosophy, Moderny20th century. 0aRealism. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aanalytic philosophy, wittgenstein, clarity, language, jargon, empiricism, realism, truth, immanence, relativity, facts, experience, linguistics, ethics, epistemology, logic, nonfiction, quine, austin, sense data, richard rorty, reductionism, john rawls, hume, kuhn, mentalism, pragmatism, logical positivism, emerson, kant, jerry fodor, noam chomsky, augustine.1 aGinsburg, Daniela.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226037554423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226037554/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles